The Skills and Talent Policy Unit is responsible for developing and coordinating policies, initiatives and services to help industry prepare for current and future skills challenges. 

  

Successful candidates will work closely with analysts in the branch by gathering and analysing economic, social and educational intelligence to help develop policies and strategies to advance Canada's talent and skills ecosystem and address employer skills needs during COVID-19 disruption. 

  

Duties and responsibilities could include:


Analysing economic, employment and skills related information, such as:


Identifying and monitoring industry focused skills challenges;
Promoting proven workplace talent solutions, such as work-integrated learning, upskilling, and employer training;
Understanding the impact that technological change, automation, and other driving forces are having on industry skills needs;
Contributing policy advice to inform government skills programming.


Undertaking policy research on a variety of topics, such as:


Supporting workers in at-risk sectors;
Upskilling of mature workers;
Solving rural and remote regional labour challenges;
Promoting skills for innovation, scale-up and technology adoption;
